{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"duration_ms":125771,"duration_api_ms":125610,"num_turns":6,"result":"Written to `/workspace/agent_output/answer.json`. Here's a summary of findings:\n\n---\n\n**Where prefix resolution happens**\n\nAll nested-blueprint URL prefix logic lives in `src/flask/sansio/blueprints.py`:\n\n- `BlueprintSetupState.__init__` (lines 72–77): reads `url_prefix` from options, falls back to `blueprint.url_prefix`, stores as `self.url_prefix`.\n- `Blueprint.register_blueprint` (line 271): only records `(blueprint, options)` in `self._blueprints` — **no prefix work here**.\n- `Blueprint.register` (lines 349–377): the actual combination site. For each nested blueprint it reads the child's prefix (from options, then from `blueprint.url_prefix`), then combines with the parent's `state.url_prefix` via a three-branch conditional.\n\n**How combination works (lines 367–374)**\n\n```\nparent prefix set  AND  child prefix set  →  join them:  /api + /users = /api/users  ✓\nparent prefix None AND  child prefix set  →  use child only:  /users  (parent lost)  ✗\nparent prefix set  AND  child prefix None →  use parent only:  /api  (child lost)  ✗\nboth None                                 →  no url_prefix key set at all             ✗\n```\n\n**When the nested prefix gets dropped**\n\nThe described scenario (`api_bp.url_prefix='/api'`, `users_bp.url_prefix='/users'`) is **handled correctly by the current code** — both prefixes are non-None so the join branch fires. The prefix is dropped under these conditions:\n\n1. The **parent blueprint has no `url_prefix`** (not set on `Blueprint(...)` and not passed to `app.register_blueprint`) — child's prefix is used alone, parent segment is missing.\n2. **Both** parent and child have no prefix — routes silently register at the root.\n\nIn all failure cases, Flask emits **no warning or exception**, making the bug silent and hard to diagnose.","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"1e100f72-f9ff-4068-8639-2